    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-03-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-03-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.248/55</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Baron <persName type="from">Amaury de La Grange</persName> to
                        the Chief of the Office of Arms and Munitions Control</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Green</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-16">March 16,
                            1938</date>.<lb/>[Received April 2.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Green</hi>: Since my return to France, I have been
                    pursuing the plan which I told you of in the conversation I had the pleasure of
                    having with you in Washington.</p>
                <pb facs="0313" n="305" xml:id="pg_305"/>
                <p>I have studied the document which you gave me, and I wonder if I understood
                    correctly wha you explained to me.</p>
                <p>On page 2, section “<hi rend="italic">g</hi>”, it is said: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Whenever the President … shall cease to grant authority to export arms,
                            etc.…”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Does this mean that no agent for the French Government could, under those
                    circumstances, buy war material in the United States, take delivery on American
                    territory, and export such war material on foreign ships?</p>
                <p>Or, does this provision merely prohibit export of war material, by American
                    citizens on American ships?</p>
                <p>I would be so grateful to you if you would be kind enough to give me your opinion
                    on this subject.</p>
                <p>Believe me [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">A. de La Grange</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Sénateur</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
